Architecture plan for issues #35-#37

Scope
- Refine the visual treatment of the existing SVG numeral rings.
- Strengthen browser coverage so the rendered Roman and Arabic numerals are
  explicitly asserted.
- Complete a polish pass across supported browsers, update the screenshot, and
  document the dual numeral rings.

Module structure and file organization
- index.html
  - No structural changes are expected unless polish reveals a small coordinate
    adjustment is needed to prevent visual collision.
  - Preserve the existing static SVG text elements and hand/tick elements.
- styles.css
  - Issue #35 owns numeral presentation: shared .numeral styling, neutral fill,
    centered SVG text, and distinct Roman/Arabic sizing.
  - Keep styling scoped to the clock SVG classes; avoid layout or framework
    changes.
- e2e/clock.spec.js
  - Issue #36 owns browser assertions for visible Roman and Arabic numeral text.
  - Keep existing hand-rotation and viewport assertions intact.
- docs/screenshot.png
  - Issue #37 refreshes the screenshot after the visual polish is complete.
- README.md
  - Issue #37 updates the project description to mention the dual numeral rings.

Shared types and contracts
- There are no new shared data types.
- The stable DOM contract remains #clock, .numeral.roman, .numeral.arabic, and
  the hand selectors #hand-hour, #hand-minute, and #hand-second.
- clock.js should remain unchanged unless a regression is found; numeral styling
  and assertions should not alter time computation or ticking behavior.

Dependencies between issues
- #35 should land first because it defines the final visual styling for the
  numeral rings.
- #36 depends on the numeral elements and styling hooks being present; it should
  assert visible Roman XII and Arabic 12 while preserving existing behavior
  checks.
- #37 depends on #35 and #36 so the screenshot and README describe the polished,
  tested state.

Key design decisions
- Keep the project plain static HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.
- Prefer SVG/CSS properties for centering and legibility rather than JavaScript
  layout work.
- Use the existing Playwright setup for cross-browser validation and screenshot
  refresh; do not add new test tooling.
- Treat visual collision as a styling/coordinate polish concern, not a reason
  to redesign the SVG clock.
